1
00:00:16,751 --> 00:00:18,050
                    [door opens]

2
00:00:18,085 --> 00:00:20,252
      See what dirt             
      you can find on her.      

3
00:00:21,455 --> 00:00:23,021
              Joy.              

4
00:00:23,057 --> 00:00:25,391
       You have a visitor.      

5
00:00:25,426 --> 00:00:27,860
      A Mr. Martin Mariner.     

6
00:00:27,895 --> 00:00:30,028
         Just your type.        

7
00:00:32,099 --> 00:00:34,566
Are you Frank Hathaway?         

8
00:00:34,602 --> 00:00:36,702
       -Are you American?       
       -Yes, sir.               

9
00:00:36,737 --> 00:00:38,404
From Nashville, Tennessee.      

10
00:00:38,439 --> 00:00:41,273
So, are you Frank Hathaway?     

11
00:00:41,308 --> 00:00:43,642
            Uh, yes.            

12
00:00:43,677 --> 00:00:45,110
Oh. Oh, Frank!                  

13
00:00:45,146 --> 00:00:46,445
-[grunts]                       
-It's so great                  

14
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:48,247
to finally meet you.            

15
00:00:48,282 --> 00:00:50,115
Or should I call you            
Francis?                        

16
00:00:50,151 --> 00:00:52,651
Oh, let me take                 
a look at you.                  

17
00:00:52,686 --> 00:00:55,454
            You have two seconds
            to let me go.       

18
00:00:55,489 --> 00:00:59,725
Oh, no way. I've been dreaming  
about this moment for years.    

19
00:00:59,760 --> 00:01:01,693
                   One... two...

20
00:01:01,729 --> 00:01:04,163
          -Frank...             
          -Easy, tiger.         

21
00:01:04,198 --> 00:01:06,298
        -I did warn him.        
        -Too much.              

22
00:01:06,333 --> 00:01:09,168
                  Frank, please.
                  That hurts.   

23
00:01:09,203 --> 00:01:10,602
                          A lot.

24
00:01:10,638 --> 00:01:11,804
      Who the hell are you?     

25
00:01:11,839 --> 00:01:13,405
                 I'm your uncle.

26
00:01:13,440 --> 00:01:15,407
              What?             

27
00:01:16,777 --> 00:01:18,343
            We're family, Frank.

28
00:01:18,379 --> 00:01:20,746
Ain't it wonderful?             

29
00:01:43,737 --> 00:01:45,337
 [Frank]                        
 What, you're my dad's brother? 

30
00:01:45,372 --> 00:01:46,572
          [Martin]              
          That's right.         

31
00:01:46,607 --> 00:01:48,507
               My mother is your
               grandmother.     

32
00:01:48,542 --> 00:01:50,409
But don't you think my dad      
might have mentioned you?       

33
00:01:50,444 --> 00:01:52,878
          He might not even know
          I exist.              

34
00:01:52,913 --> 00:01:54,680
         I was adopted at birth.

35
00:01:54,715 --> 00:01:57,015
     I was raised by a wonderful
     British couple             

36
00:01:57,051 --> 00:01:58,850
                   who moved out
                   to Tennessee.

37
00:01:58,886 --> 00:02:03,388
 But now they've both passed,   
 I'm tracing my blood relations.

38
00:02:03,424 --> 00:02:04,590
               And you, Frank...

39
00:02:04,625 --> 00:02:05,691
                 [clicks tongue]

40
00:02:05,726 --> 00:02:07,626
             ...you are my first
             discovery.         

41
00:02:07,661 --> 00:02:09,027
Cobblers.                       

42
00:02:09,063 --> 00:02:10,896
            Well, I'll show you.

43
00:02:12,233 --> 00:02:14,366
         Now, birth certificate.

44
00:02:14,401 --> 00:02:15,467
           And that's my mother.

45
00:02:15,502 --> 00:02:18,170
      [Lu]                      
      "Elizabeth Hathaway."     

46
00:02:18,205 --> 00:02:19,705
       Is that your grandmother?

47
00:02:19,740 --> 00:02:20,973
    Well, it's a common name.   

48
00:02:21,008 --> 00:02:23,108
      [Lu]                      
      Maiden name: Foster.      

49
00:02:23,143 --> 00:02:25,377
I haven't got a clue            
about maiden names.             

50
00:02:25,412 --> 00:02:27,179
She died years                  
before I was born.              

51
00:02:27,214 --> 00:02:28,880
      How come the father's     
      not listed?               

52
00:02:28,916 --> 00:02:33,418
 Well, young man, it's very     
 possible that I'm a love child.

53
00:02:33,454 --> 00:02:34,786
Oh, great.                      

54
00:02:34,822 --> 00:02:37,022
So now you're calling my nana   
a tramp as well as a liar.      

55
00:02:37,057 --> 00:02:40,759
  Here's our family tree, Frank.

56
00:02:40,794 --> 00:02:44,029
    I only managed to go back   
    to the 17th century.        

57
00:02:44,064 --> 00:02:46,264
           [Sebastian]          
           Incredible.          

58
00:02:46,300 --> 00:02:48,700
So, 1953.                       

59
00:02:48,736 --> 00:02:50,369
Is that when                    
your nan died?                  

60
00:02:50,404 --> 00:02:52,371
  Well, around that time, yes.  

61
00:02:52,406 --> 00:02:55,674
        I can't find Elizabeth's
        death certificate       

62
00:02:55,709 --> 00:02:57,943
                 to confirm     
                 the actual day.

63
00:02:57,978 --> 00:03:02,247
 But since I know that my mother
 died in childbirth,            

64
00:03:02,282 --> 00:03:07,019
  got to be my birthday:        
  4th of July, Independence Day.

65
00:03:07,054 --> 00:03:08,620
  That's great detective work,  
  Martin, yeah.                 

66
00:03:08,655 --> 00:03:10,222
       -Thank you, ma'am.       
       -[Frank] Ah!             

67
00:03:10,257 --> 00:03:13,191
     She died in childbirth,    
     did you say?               

68
00:03:13,227 --> 00:03:14,459
                   That's right.

69
00:03:14,495 --> 00:03:16,862
Because my nana died            
in a car crash.                 

70
00:03:16,897 --> 00:03:19,264
      Are you absolutely certain
      about that, Frank?        

71
00:03:19,299 --> 00:03:22,501
   Because my adoptive parents  
   were told that my mother died

72
00:03:22,536 --> 00:03:23,969
             giving birth to me.

73
00:03:24,004 --> 00:03:26,405
   It's the only thing about    
   my nana that I am sure of.   

74
00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:27,672
           Ow, Frank!           

75
00:03:27,708 --> 00:03:29,341
    [Frank]                     
    Wrong Elizabeth Hathaway.   

76
00:03:29,376 --> 00:03:31,510
 Oh, what a shame. There we are.
 Let me help you with these.    

77
00:03:31,545 --> 00:03:34,279
            -Frank...           
            -Come on.           

78
00:03:34,314 --> 00:03:36,081
  [Martin] We're related, Frank.
  I can feel it.                

79
00:03:36,116 --> 00:03:37,382
         [Frank]                
         Apparently not.        

80
00:03:37,418 --> 00:03:38,884
     At least let me buy you    
     a coffee.                  

81
00:03:38,919 --> 00:03:40,519
Come on.                        

82
00:03:40,554 --> 00:03:43,889
[in mock American accent]       
Thanks for stopping by!         

83
00:03:51,532 --> 00:03:52,898
              What?             

84
00:03:54,735 --> 00:03:56,268
        He was obviously        
        a con man.              

85
00:03:56,303 --> 00:03:59,070
          What's he after, then?
          Your fortune?         

86
00:04:00,741 --> 00:04:02,207
             [sighs]            

87
00:04:06,447 --> 00:04:08,079
          So, when did this Lola
          start work here?      

88
00:04:08,115 --> 00:04:09,381
[Leon]                          
Three months ago.               

89
00:04:09,416 --> 00:04:11,049
I gave her the job.             

90
00:04:11,084 --> 00:04:12,451
I honestly thought              
I could trust her.              

91
00:04:12,486 --> 00:04:13,985
That's what hurts               
the most.                       

92
00:04:14,021 --> 00:04:16,388
  -Aye. When was this accident? 
  -[Leon] A month ago.          

93
00:04:16,423 --> 00:04:18,423
  I found Lola out in the back, 
  screaming.                    

94
00:04:18,459 --> 00:04:20,425
      She claimed a box         
      of Shakespeare busts      

95
00:04:20,461 --> 00:04:22,194
    had fallen off a trolley    
    and landed on her foot.     

96
00:04:22,229 --> 00:04:24,463
   -[chuckles]                  
   -[Diana] Next thing we know  

97
00:04:24,498 --> 00:04:26,665
she's on crutches and suing us  
for compensation.               

98
00:04:26,700 --> 00:04:27,966
          No witnesses,         
          I take it?            

99
00:04:28,001 --> 00:04:29,134
[Leon]                          
Of course not.                  

100
00:04:29,169 --> 00:04:31,102
    [Lu]                        
    Twisted ankle ligaments.    

101
00:04:31,138 --> 00:04:33,638
    The only thing twisted      
    is that girl's morality.    

102
00:04:33,674 --> 00:04:35,607
   So you want us to prove      
   she was faking the injury?   

103
00:04:35,642 --> 00:04:39,044
Photos, videos.                 
You do whatever it takes.       

104
00:04:39,079 --> 00:04:40,245
    Surveillance isn't cheap.   

105
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:41,613
           And neither are      
           compensation payouts.

106
00:04:41,648 --> 00:04:43,849
       -Fair enough.            
       -The awful thing is      

107
00:04:43,884 --> 00:04:45,250
the hearing's been              
brought forward.                

108
00:04:45,285 --> 00:04:46,518
It's now next week.             

109
00:04:46,553 --> 00:04:48,386
             We will get on this
             right away.        

110
00:04:48,422 --> 00:04:49,754
                    Don't worry.

111
00:04:51,592 --> 00:04:54,426
 [Frank]                        
 I think you put a few too many 
 noughts on there by mistake.   

112
00:04:54,461 --> 00:04:56,027
            [laughs]            

113
00:04:56,063 --> 00:04:57,963
Frank.                          

114
00:04:57,998 --> 00:04:59,764
          Yeah. Just...         

115
00:05:09,076 --> 00:05:10,208
           [Lu sighs]           

116
00:05:10,244 --> 00:05:12,377
       [Lu]                     
       He seemed credible.      

117
00:05:12,412 --> 00:05:15,280
   [Frank]                      
   My nan died in a car crash.  

118
00:05:16,149 --> 00:05:17,916
    What if they lied to you?   

119
00:05:17,951 --> 00:05:19,184
       That happens a lot       
       in family.               

120
00:05:19,219 --> 00:05:21,453
                 I'm not related
                 to that nutter.

121
00:05:23,090 --> 00:05:24,956
           Oh, hello.           

122
00:05:31,198 --> 00:05:34,466
     So far, so convincing.     

123
00:05:53,086 --> 00:05:54,452
              Now?              

124
00:05:55,756 --> 00:05:57,355
             [sighs]            

125
00:06:05,232 --> 00:06:06,831
        This seat taken?        

126
00:06:06,867 --> 00:06:09,334
          -Go ahead.            
          -Oh, thanks.          

127
00:06:10,270 --> 00:06:11,603
            Do you mind if I...?

128
00:06:14,007 --> 00:06:15,807
      They're a right pain,     
      those things, aren't they?

129
00:06:15,842 --> 00:06:17,842
    -Yeah, I'm sick of them.    
    -Yeah.                      

130
00:06:17,878 --> 00:06:19,944
              No, I broke my toe
              last year.        

131
00:06:19,980 --> 00:06:21,312
           Fell down the stairs.

132
00:06:21,348 --> 00:06:24,282
        I was off my head.      
        It was totally my fault.

133
00:06:24,317 --> 00:06:26,017
Twisted ligaments.              

134
00:06:26,053 --> 00:06:27,318
                      Oh, right.

135
00:06:27,354 --> 00:06:29,654
   -How?                        
   -This box fell on my foot.   

136
00:06:29,690 --> 00:06:31,289
                       Oh, ouch.
                       [laughs] 

137
00:06:31,324 --> 00:06:33,024
               Was that at home?

138
00:06:33,060 --> 00:06:35,226
Work.                           

139
00:06:35,262 --> 00:06:37,762
      Oh, well, I hope you get  
      plenty of sympathy for it.

140
00:06:37,798 --> 00:06:39,397
Not exactly.                    

141
00:06:39,433 --> 00:06:41,166
           No? What do you mean?

142
00:06:41,201 --> 00:06:43,134
Well, my bosses thought         
I was lying, which was nice.    

143
00:06:43,170 --> 00:06:45,103
    -Didn't even get an apology.
    -Oh, honestly.              

144
00:06:45,138 --> 00:06:47,639
         The things employers   
         get away with now, hey?

145
00:06:49,743 --> 00:06:50,909
         Hello, darling.        

146
00:06:50,944 --> 00:06:52,343
          Small world.          

147
00:06:52,379 --> 00:06:55,847
    Oh, I love the new look.    

148
00:06:57,050 --> 00:06:58,349
        I'm Gloria, Lu's friend.

149
00:06:58,385 --> 00:07:00,552
      -Lola.                    
      -We've only just met.     

150
00:07:00,587 --> 00:07:01,753
             Really?            

151
00:07:01,788 --> 00:07:03,154
       Okay if I join you?      

152
00:07:03,190 --> 00:07:05,256
No, I'm not staying.            

153
00:07:08,028 --> 00:07:09,094
        What am I doing?        

154
00:07:09,129 --> 00:07:12,197
        I've got Carlos coming--
        oh, in 10 minutes.      

155
00:07:13,233 --> 00:07:14,599
           My masseur.          

156
00:07:14,634 --> 00:07:15,834
         Beautiful man,         

157
00:07:15,869 --> 00:07:18,470
    and surprisingly punctual   
    for a Brazilian.            

158
00:07:18,505 --> 00:07:20,071
        Nice to meet you.       

159
00:07:20,107 --> 00:07:21,840
        See you soon, Lu.       

160
00:07:21,875 --> 00:07:23,374
              -Bye.             
              -Bye.             

161
00:07:24,711 --> 00:07:27,112
       -I should go, too.       
       -Oh, right. Okay.        

162
00:07:40,660 --> 00:07:42,994
    Yeah, as soon as we catch   
    her out, Mr. Tarsich,       

163
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:45,330
        I will call you         
        right away, okay?       

164
00:07:45,365 --> 00:07:46,731
             I will.            

165
00:07:46,766 --> 00:07:48,299
         Yeah, bye. Bye.        

166
00:07:49,436 --> 00:07:51,736
   That is the third time       
   he's called already today.   

167
00:07:51,771 --> 00:07:53,571
            It's from Sebastian.

168
00:07:53,607 --> 00:07:56,107
    "According to our contact   
    at the credit check company,

169
00:07:56,142 --> 00:07:59,477
        Lola Gower owes over    
        20,000 in payday loans."

170
00:07:59,513 --> 00:08:01,546
Then she needs                  
this compensation.              

171
00:08:01,581 --> 00:08:04,916
       Well, if she's faking it,
       she's doing a decent job.

172
00:08:04,951 --> 00:08:06,184
           Oh, hello.           

173
00:08:06,219 --> 00:08:08,186
        He looks pleased        
        with himself.           

174
00:08:23,336 --> 00:08:25,470
       [Frank]                  
       I don't believe it.      

175
00:08:25,505 --> 00:08:26,638
What?                           

176
00:08:26,673 --> 00:08:28,273
                      That Yank.

177
00:08:28,308 --> 00:08:30,341
        He's stalking me.       

178
00:08:32,479 --> 00:08:33,912
                         [sighs]

179
00:08:33,947 --> 00:08:35,546
                         Weirdo.

180
00:08:41,321 --> 00:08:44,622
 All you need to do is find out 
 the date your nan died.        

181
00:08:44,658 --> 00:08:48,593
Then if it's not July 4th, 1953,
you're in the clear, aren't you?

182
00:08:48,628 --> 00:08:51,396
    [Frank]                     
    How am I going to do that   
    with Mom and Dad gone?      

183
00:08:53,767 --> 00:08:56,100
     Sounds like it's a job     
     for Frank Hathaway.        

184
00:08:56,136 --> 00:08:59,070
              Frank Hathaway    
              already has a job.

185
00:08:59,105 --> 00:09:01,339
        Watching somebody       
        watch telly.            

186
00:09:02,375 --> 00:09:05,476
Oh, it's going to be            
a long night.                   

187
00:09:27,867 --> 00:09:29,400
       [cell phone rings]       

188
00:09:31,338 --> 00:09:33,471
Oh! It's him again.             

189
00:09:33,506 --> 00:09:35,373
             -Again?            
             -Again.            

190
00:09:37,477 --> 00:09:40,078
Hello, Mr. Tarsich.             

191
00:09:40,113 --> 00:09:41,779
         [Leon, on phone]       
        <i> Anything?</i>              

192
00:09:41,815 --> 00:09:44,148
    No, she's still in her flat,
    I'm afraid.                 

193
00:09:44,184 --> 00:09:46,484
She hasn't left since lunchtime.

194
00:09:46,519 --> 00:09:48,052
       <i> This is pointless.</i>      

195
00:09:48,088 --> 00:09:50,822
 Yeah, well,                    
 as I said before, Mr. Tarsich, 

196
00:09:50,857 --> 00:09:52,457
      patience is the key.      

197
00:09:52,492 --> 00:09:54,392
     <i> You don't understand.</i>     

198
00:09:54,427 --> 00:09:56,127
       <i> We're not insured.</i>      

199
00:09:56,162 --> 00:09:58,463
   <i> Well, not with</i>              
   <i> the right policy, anyway.</i>   

200
00:09:58,498 --> 00:10:00,164
               Oh.              

201
00:10:00,200 --> 00:10:02,166
     <i> I haven't told Diana,</i>     
     <i> but if that girl wins,</i>    

202
00:10:02,202 --> 00:10:03,367
      <i> it could cripple us.</i>     

203
00:10:03,403 --> 00:10:04,969
            -[sighs]            
            -I see.             

204
00:10:05,004 --> 00:10:06,504
         <i> It's my fault.</i>        

205
00:10:06,539 --> 00:10:08,439
     <i> I was halfway through</i>     
     <i> filling in the form,</i>      

206
00:10:08,475 --> 00:10:09,841
   <i> but then I had to go away</i>   
   <i> for work.</i>                   

207
00:10:09,876 --> 00:10:11,375
             [Lu]               
             Right.             

208
00:10:17,350 --> 00:10:19,650
       [gasps and giggles]      
       Oh.                      

209
00:10:21,921 --> 00:10:25,323
Double bacon, double egg,       
double ketchup for the vitamins.

210
00:10:25,358 --> 00:10:27,225
                      Thank you.

211
00:10:27,260 --> 00:10:28,526
No sign of life?                

212
00:10:28,561 --> 00:10:29,660
               Mm.              

213
00:10:29,696 --> 00:10:32,029
I think we need to step up      
our coverage.                   

214
00:10:32,065 --> 00:10:34,632
Let's see if the clients will   
stump up for a hidden camera.   

215
00:10:34,667 --> 00:10:35,867
               Mm.              

216
00:10:35,902 --> 00:10:37,602
            -For me?            
            -Yeah.              

217
00:10:37,637 --> 00:10:38,970
                            Hmm.

218
00:10:43,510 --> 00:10:45,409
Is-- oh.                        

219
00:10:57,690 --> 00:10:59,390
          Cheers, Ajay.         

220
00:11:19,078 --> 00:11:20,745
         [rattles door]         

221
00:11:23,716 --> 00:11:25,883
     [distant police siren]     

222
00:11:25,919 --> 00:11:27,685
         [camera clicks]        

223
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:29,720
        [car doors close]       

224
00:11:32,992 --> 00:11:35,526
                     [footsteps]

225
00:11:35,562 --> 00:11:37,428
Oh, look,                       
it's the marshmallow twins.     

226
00:11:37,463 --> 00:11:39,096
           -Hi, Frank.          
           -Hello.              

227
00:11:39,132 --> 00:11:40,965
             Frank.             

228
00:11:41,901 --> 00:11:43,434
Ah, Christina.                  

229
00:11:43,469 --> 00:11:44,769
             Frank.             

230
00:11:44,804 --> 00:11:47,038
          Didn't take you       
          as the gift shop type.

231
00:11:47,073 --> 00:11:49,974
       Yeah, I ran out          
       of Waterlily soap.       

232
00:11:50,009 --> 00:11:51,842
[chuckles and clears throat]    

233
00:11:51,878 --> 00:11:54,378
Fraud claim involving           
an ex-member of staff.          

234
00:11:54,414 --> 00:11:56,447
I came to see my client.        

235
00:11:56,482 --> 00:11:59,216
      Going to have to talk     
      to the husband now.       

236
00:11:59,252 --> 00:12:01,052
     And you can scratch her    
     off the list,              

237
00:12:01,087 --> 00:12:03,621
             the girl we've been
             trailing.          

238
00:12:03,656 --> 00:12:04,755
             Thanks.            

239
00:12:04,791 --> 00:12:06,357
And given it's a robbery        
gone wrong...                   

240
00:12:06,392 --> 00:12:07,591
                          Is it?

241
00:12:07,627 --> 00:12:09,226
Back door forced.               

242
00:12:09,262 --> 00:12:10,461
Signs of a struggle.            

243
