00:22:06,925 --> 00:22:08,792
Come on, how much               
do you want for it?             

484
00:22:08,827 --> 00:22:13,029
  Hey, as I said,               
  I don't know nothing about it.

485
00:22:13,065 --> 00:22:15,398
[Frank]                         
I hear Lola's dropped the claim.

486
00:22:15,434 --> 00:22:17,200
        -Do you work out?       
        -You...                 

487
00:22:17,235 --> 00:22:18,668
       -Who are you?            
       -[Frank] Who am I?       

488
00:22:18,704 --> 00:22:20,470
  That's a fundamental question.
  Who is anyone?                

489
00:22:20,505 --> 00:22:21,738
                    Who are you?

490
00:22:21,773 --> 00:22:23,306
            [grunts]            

491
00:22:23,342 --> 00:22:24,874
      [Phil]                    
      Tell me who sent you,     

492
00:22:24,910 --> 00:22:26,009
  or I'll break your arm in two.

493
00:22:26,044 --> 00:22:27,310
   [Frank]                      
   You've got a temper on you.  

494
00:22:27,346 --> 00:22:28,845
         -[bone cracks]         
         -Ow!                   

495
00:22:28,880 --> 00:22:30,146
           [groaning]           

496
00:22:30,182 --> 00:22:33,383
         Oh, you brute.         

497
00:22:33,418 --> 00:22:34,684
          I'm a copper.         

498
00:22:34,720 --> 00:22:35,919
              Of course you are.

499
00:22:35,954 --> 00:22:37,120
             Try me.            

500
00:22:37,155 --> 00:22:39,022
           [groaning]           

501
00:22:41,560 --> 00:22:42,926
          Cheers, Phil.         

502
00:22:45,864 --> 00:22:48,031
Don't point at me.              

503
00:22:51,336 --> 00:22:52,769
        [car door closes]       

504
00:22:52,804 --> 00:22:54,537
         [engine starts]        

505
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:00,310
                        [grunts]

506
00:23:00,345 --> 00:23:03,446
So, now you know                
how Martin felt.                

507
00:23:03,482 --> 00:23:05,014
        Thanks for the sympathy.

508
00:23:05,050 --> 00:23:06,449
                        [groans]
                        Well?   

509
00:23:06,485 --> 00:23:10,420
Found this in the glove         
compartment.                    

510
00:23:10,455 --> 00:23:12,622
             Ah. Classic burner.

511
00:23:18,230 --> 00:23:20,263
            We've found our "P."

512
00:23:20,298 --> 00:23:21,598
Yeah.                           

513
00:23:21,633 --> 00:23:23,700
     [Marlowe] We located       
     a couple of bank notes     

514
00:23:23,735 --> 00:23:25,902
       with blood on them       
       in his flat,             

515
00:23:25,937 --> 00:23:27,737
      and we also found him     
      on CCTV                   

516
00:23:27,772 --> 00:23:30,106
in the vicinity of the gift shop
at the time of the murder.      

517
00:23:30,142 --> 00:23:32,675
      And he's got previous     
      for robbery.              

518
00:23:32,711 --> 00:23:33,943
How do you know that?           

519
00:23:33,979 --> 00:23:35,812
     Because some people in here
     still rate me.             

520
00:23:35,847 --> 00:23:39,048
Never knew you were             
so sensitive.                   

521
00:23:40,385 --> 00:23:43,119
 So Diana gets Phil over to tell
 him she's ending the affair.   

522
00:23:43,155 --> 00:23:45,755
 He takes it badly, whacks her  
 on the head with a big fossil. 

523
00:23:45,790 --> 00:23:47,590
And then he staged              
a robbery.                      

524
00:23:48,994 --> 00:23:51,194
Go on then, say it.             

525
00:23:53,598 --> 00:23:55,298
        I'm not sure it was Phil
        who killed her.         

526
00:23:55,333 --> 00:23:57,433
              What?             

527
00:23:57,469 --> 00:23:58,935
                 Well, according
                 to the phone,  

528
00:23:58,970 --> 00:24:02,305
       Diana wasn't his only bit
       on the side.             

529
00:24:02,340 --> 00:24:04,207
Okay. So?                       

530
00:24:04,242 --> 00:24:08,244
      So why would her ending it
      make him so angry?        

531
00:24:08,280 --> 00:24:10,547
         Frank, I'm out.        

532
00:24:10,582 --> 00:24:12,248
                        [groans]

533
00:24:12,284 --> 00:24:14,551
[whispering]                    
He's a big fan of yours.        

534
00:24:14,586 --> 00:24:17,053
He can't wait to get back       
to your search.                 

535
00:24:17,088 --> 00:24:19,856
       Well, every silver lining
       has a cloud.             

536
00:24:19,891 --> 00:24:21,157
[laughs]                        

537
00:24:21,192 --> 00:24:24,227
          Ah, ah. Come on, walk.

538
00:24:24,262 --> 00:24:26,029
          [Frank sighs]         

539
00:24:27,499 --> 00:24:30,233
     [Gloria] It was when Lu    
     gave me that look.         

540
00:24:30,268 --> 00:24:31,701
[laughs]                        

541
00:24:31,736 --> 00:24:33,303
           That was the moment  
           I realized I'd walked

542
00:24:33,338 --> 00:24:35,104
           into a secret        
           undercover operation,

543
00:24:35,140 --> 00:24:36,906
             and I nearly       
             had a heart attack.

544
00:24:36,942 --> 00:24:40,076
Well, Lu says you covered it    
like Dame Judi herself.         

545
00:24:41,246 --> 00:24:42,979
             I wasn't that good.

546
00:24:44,683 --> 00:24:45,848
  One of my regulars, that is.  

547
00:24:45,884 --> 00:24:47,417
       [Sebastian]              
       What, the murderer?      

548
00:24:47,452 --> 00:24:49,986
        [Gloria]                
        No. The husband.        

549
00:24:50,021 --> 00:24:51,654
         I didn't know          
         his real name.         

550
00:24:51,690 --> 00:24:53,022
           Poor bloke.          

551
00:24:53,058 --> 00:24:55,625
Well, what name                 
did he use with you?            

552
00:24:55,660 --> 00:24:57,260
                          Linda.

553
00:24:57,295 --> 00:24:58,861
Linda?                          

554
00:25:03,368 --> 00:25:05,902
[Frank]                         
How many more parishes to check?

555
00:25:05,937 --> 00:25:08,037
Uh... 103.                      

556
00:25:08,073 --> 00:25:09,238
       [cell phone rings]       

557
00:25:09,274 --> 00:25:10,840
                             Oh.

558
00:25:10,875 --> 00:25:13,142
          I've got to take this.

559
00:25:13,178 --> 00:25:14,777
I'll meet you outside.          

560
00:25:16,948 --> 00:25:18,982
          -Yes?                 
          -Having fun?          

561
00:25:19,017 --> 00:25:21,117
          -No.                  
          -Family, eh?          

562
00:25:21,152 --> 00:25:22,885
Well, I've worked out           
where Leon Tarsich              

563
00:25:22,921 --> 00:25:25,021
really spent                    
those Friday nights.            

564
00:25:25,056 --> 00:25:26,522
                    Well, go on.

565
00:25:26,558 --> 00:25:27,991
The Moody Mule.                 

566
00:25:28,026 --> 00:25:29,425
                  You're joking.

567
00:25:29,461 --> 00:25:33,062
 Which rather begs the question,
 did the wife know?             

568
00:25:34,032 --> 00:25:35,098
                        Hang on.

569
00:25:35,133 --> 00:25:37,100
       -It's Friday today.      
       -Exactly.                

570
00:25:37,135 --> 00:25:38,968
Second of the month.            

571
00:25:39,003 --> 00:25:41,771
    -[indistinct chattering]    
    -[jazzy music playing]      

572
00:26:02,927 --> 00:26:08,131
      ♪ The poet speaks         
      But no one listens ♪      

573
00:26:13,538 --> 00:26:14,937
                             Hi.

574
00:26:17,442 --> 00:26:18,975
                      I'm Adele.

575
00:26:20,145 --> 00:26:21,611
Linda.                          

576
00:26:24,516 --> 00:26:26,282
Can I get another one,          
Gina, please?                   

577
00:26:26,317 --> 00:26:28,451
        -Okay.                  
        -You celebrating?       

578
00:26:29,454 --> 00:26:31,387
       Or drowning your sorrows?

579
00:26:33,892 --> 00:26:35,625
Bit of a week.                  

580
00:26:37,328 --> 00:26:38,795
            Death in the family.

581
00:26:38,830 --> 00:26:40,830
No.                             

582
00:26:40,865 --> 00:26:43,833
Oh, that's awful.               
I'm so sorry.                   

583
00:26:45,203 --> 00:26:47,970
I lost my dog recently.         

584
00:26:52,911 --> 00:26:54,710
Were you very close?            

585
00:26:56,781 --> 00:26:58,648
              Yeah.             

586
00:27:02,387 --> 00:27:04,053
             And no.            

587
00:27:04,989 --> 00:27:06,322
Thank you.                      

588
00:27:12,330 --> 00:27:13,763
It was my wife.                 

589
00:27:13,798 --> 00:27:16,632
                    Oh, my gosh.

590
00:27:20,338 --> 00:27:22,071
               Had she been ill?

591
00:27:24,909 --> 00:27:26,709
              Yeah.             

592
00:27:26,744 --> 00:27:28,611
Even so.                        

593
00:27:29,847 --> 00:27:31,781
Poor you.                       

594
00:27:33,751 --> 00:27:35,685
      Part of me feels relieved.

595
00:27:35,720 --> 00:27:37,920
Well, if she'd been ill         
for a long time...              

596
00:27:37,956 --> 00:27:39,722
                  It's not that.

597
00:27:41,526 --> 00:27:43,593
She couldn't accept this.       

598
00:27:43,628 --> 00:27:45,294
                             No?

599
00:27:47,098 --> 00:27:49,599
Found out a few months back.    

600
00:27:49,634 --> 00:27:51,400
Two weeks later,                
she started sleeping            

601
00:27:51,436 --> 00:27:52,768
with an employee's              
boyfriend.                      

602
00:27:52,804 --> 00:27:55,271
                   Unbelievable.

603
00:27:56,641 --> 00:27:58,374
That's not the worst            
of it, though.                  

604
00:28:02,013 --> 00:28:03,412
                     [Sebastian]
                     Oh.        

605
00:28:03,448 --> 00:28:05,214
                From cigarettes?

606
00:28:08,820 --> 00:28:10,753
She burned you?                 

607
00:28:15,326 --> 00:28:18,127
    So, Diana was physically    
    abusing Leon                

608
00:28:18,162 --> 00:28:20,896
    because he wasn't the man   
    she thought she married.    

609
00:28:20,932 --> 00:28:23,065
And he knew                     
about her affair.               

610
00:28:23,101 --> 00:28:25,368
      I'd have been out of there
      like a shot.              

611
00:28:25,403 --> 00:28:26,669
He had no money, though.        

612
00:28:26,704 --> 00:28:28,971
      Yeah, he's got plenty now,
      hasn't he?                

613
00:28:29,007 --> 00:28:30,873
       So that's a double motive
       for murder.              

614
00:28:30,908 --> 00:28:32,208
               Revenge and cash.

615
00:28:32,243 --> 00:28:34,176
           Plus a lack of alibi.

616
00:28:34,212 --> 00:28:36,579
Except we know he didn't do it, 
because when Diana was killed,  

617
00:28:36,614 --> 00:28:38,581
he was on the phone to me.      

618
00:28:38,616 --> 00:28:41,050
    -We've missed something.    
    -What?                      

619
00:28:41,085 --> 00:28:43,386
       I don't know,            
       but we've got to find it.

620
00:28:43,421 --> 00:28:45,621
        I'll speak to you later.

621
00:28:45,656 --> 00:28:46,756
        [phone beeps off]       

622
00:28:46,791 --> 00:28:49,425
            So, was he impressed
            with my handiwork?  

623
00:28:49,460 --> 00:28:51,293
           Yes. Very.           

624
00:28:51,329 --> 00:28:52,461
          He's... yeah.         

625
00:28:52,497 --> 00:28:54,764
     He didn't say anything,    
     did he?                    

626
00:28:55,600 --> 00:28:56,866
               That's all right.

627
00:28:56,901 --> 00:28:58,834
     I only do this job         
     for the lavish salary.     

628
00:28:58,870 --> 00:29:01,103
       -[cell phone rings]      
       -Oh.                     

629
00:29:01,973 --> 00:29:03,572
                Lola's curtains.

630
00:29:03,608 --> 00:29:05,274
Sorry, what?                    

631
00:29:05,309 --> 00:29:08,978
 Who has a night in by the telly
 with the curtains wide open?   

632
00:29:10,181 --> 00:29:11,947
Maybe she's                     
claustrophobic.                 

633
00:29:11,983 --> 00:29:14,150
                Maybe she wanted
                to be seen.     

634
00:29:14,185 --> 00:29:15,618
By who?                         

635
00:29:15,653 --> 00:29:18,587
         I haven't got that far.

636
00:29:18,623 --> 00:29:19,655
             I'll see you later.

637
00:29:19,690 --> 00:29:21,524
               Perhaps she's    
               an exhibitionist.

638
00:29:21,559 --> 00:29:23,058
Well, it wasn't much            
of a show.                      

639
00:29:23,094 --> 00:29:25,628
 All she did was get up a couple
 of times to get the remote.    

640
00:29:36,641 --> 00:29:38,407
         What if we were        
         the audience?          

641
00:29:38,443 --> 00:29:39,942
                         [sighs]

642
00:29:43,147 --> 00:29:45,080
                 It's all right.
                 I trust you.   

643
00:29:45,116 --> 00:29:46,615
Oh, thanks, Frank.              

644
00:29:49,353 --> 00:29:51,053
               What do they call
               this place?      

645
00:29:51,088 --> 00:29:52,488
Oh, uh...                       

646
00:29:55,359 --> 00:29:57,326
Risley Cross.                   

647
00:29:58,963 --> 00:30:00,896
     I've been here before.     

648
00:30:02,900 --> 00:30:04,066
            -Gloria.            
            -Oh!                

649
00:30:04,101 --> 00:30:05,267
    Oh, sorry. Leon Tarsich,    

650
00:30:05,303 --> 00:30:07,269
    he hired woman's clothes    
    from you, is that right?    

651
00:30:07,305 --> 00:30:09,238
          All the time.         

652
00:30:09,273 --> 00:30:11,073
      Dresses. Hats. Shoes.     

653
00:30:11,108 --> 00:30:12,641
           -Wigs?               
           -Of course.          

654
00:30:12,677 --> 00:30:14,109
         He borrowed one        
         last week.             

655
00:30:14,145 --> 00:30:15,744
                      Which one?

656
00:30:15,780 --> 00:30:17,313
              Oh...             

657
00:30:23,988 --> 00:30:25,321
                         [sighs]

658
00:30:25,356 --> 00:30:27,256
         Did he ask specifically
         for long, blonde hair? 

659
00:30:27,291 --> 00:30:28,858
        Oh, he insisted.        

660
00:30:28,893 --> 00:30:31,193
      But to be honest,         
      I was quite surprised     

661
00:30:31,229 --> 00:30:33,162
         when he chose          
         this old thing.        

662
00:30:33,197 --> 00:30:34,930
              Ooh.              

663
00:30:38,569 --> 00:30:40,569
            [knocks]            

664
00:30:46,744 --> 00:30:48,344
[Frank]                         
Miss Whetton?                   

665
00:30:48,379 --> 00:30:50,479
              Yes?              

666
00:30:50,514 --> 00:30:53,015
         We were told that you  
         were the church warden.

667
00:30:53,050 --> 00:30:55,184
Yes, that's right.              
Morning, Vicar.                 

668
00:30:55,219 --> 00:30:57,019
          Morning, Miss Whetton.

669
00:30:57,054 --> 00:30:59,021
     I wonder if you could help.

670
00:30:59,056 --> 00:31:00,990
      We're trying to find out  
      whether a relation of mine

671
00:31:01,025 --> 00:31:02,891
                 is buried here 
                 in the village.

672
00:31:02,927 --> 00:31:05,628
Might we have a look            
at the parish burial records?   

673
00:31:05,663 --> 00:31:09,531
 Ah, well, the register         
 actually is held at Hardleton. 

674
00:31:09,567 --> 00:31:11,100
     It's the next village.     

675
00:31:11,135 --> 00:31:12,568
               Ah.              

676
00:31:12,603 --> 00:31:15,838
 But there's only one graveyard 
 here in this village.          

677
00:31:15,873 --> 00:31:17,840
It's behind                     
the church there.               

678
00:31:17,875 --> 00:31:20,242
 Great, well, we'll take a look.
 Thank you.                     

679
00:31:20,278 --> 00:31:23,212
     Right. Well, I...          
     I might remember them.     

680
00:31:23,247 --> 00:31:24,480
           [chuckles]           

681
00:31:24,515 --> 00:31:26,582
     I've lived all my life     
     in this village.           

682
00:31:26,617 --> 00:31:30,452
     And my father was vicar    
     of that church.            

683
00:31:30,488 --> 00:31:33,822
      Great. Well, we're looking
      for my grandmother.       

684
00:31:33,858 --> 00:31:35,491
She was called                  
Elizabeth Hathaway.             

685
00:31:35,526 --> 00:31:36,892
Died in 1953.                   

686
00:31:36,927 --> 00:31:39,662
     Yeah, we think             
     she might be my mother.    

687
00:31:39,697 --> 00:31:41,997
               Ah.              

688
00:31:44,001 --> 00:31:45,167
          The name's...         

689
00:31:45,202 --> 00:31:47,336
   it's not ringing any bells.  

690
00:31:47,371 --> 00:31:48,971
             Sorry.             

691
00:31:49,006 --> 00:31:50,406
       Good luck, though.       

692
00:31:57,715 --> 00:31:59,548
          She knew her.         

693
00:32:06,524 --> 00:32:08,390
      Feel familiar, Frank?     

694
00:32:09,527 --> 00:32:11,694
I'd be lying                    
if I said yes.                  

695
00:32:17,668 --> 00:32:19,001
           Found her.           

696
00:32:19,036 --> 00:32:20,369
                         Really?

697
00:32:20,404 --> 00:32:22,071
              Ooh.              

698
00:32:22,106 --> 00:32:24,540
   Does it say when she died?   

699
00:32:24,575 --> 00:32:26,241
It does, yeah.                  

700
00:32:28,212 --> 00:32:30,145
        [Martin]                
        February 11th...        

701
00:32:31,382 --> 00:32:33,082
              1952.             

702
00:32:33,117 --> 00:32:34,450
   [Frank]                      
   Year before you were born.   

703
00:32:34,485 --> 00:32:36,018
                         [sighs]

704
00:32:37,788 --> 00:32:39,555
                   It's not her.

705
00:32:45,396 --> 00:32:46,929
       You find what            
       you're looking for?      

706
00:32:49,066 --> 00:32:51,834
     We did, unfortunately.     

707
00:32:54,605 --> 00:32:56,839
Well, here--                    

708
00:32:56,874 --> 00:32:59,308
here's a little something       
for your journey.               

709
00:32:59,343 --> 00:33:01,743
               Oh, gosh.        
               Thank you, ma'am.

710
00:33:09,887 --> 00:33:11,453
You...                          

711
00:33:11,489 --> 00:33:13,856
you knew my grandmother,        
didn't you?                     

712
00:33:16,427 --> 00:33:18,527
       She was a friend of mine.

713
00:33:19,530 --> 00:33:21,230
Why didn't you tell us?         

714
00:33:21,265 --> 00:33:22,631
                  It's better...

715
00:33:25,336 --> 00:33:29,638
       I left something on...   
       on the st-- on the stove.

716
00:33:34,311 --> 00:33:35,944
               What a kind lady.

717
00:33:35,980 --> 00:33:37,546
[door closes]                   

718
00:33:42,253 --> 00:33:43,352
All right, Bab.                 

719
00:33:43,387 --> 00:33:44,686
Here to read                    
your gas meter.                 

720
00:33:44,722 --> 00:33:46,555
                  Are you?      
                  Sure, come in.

721
00:33:49,927 --> 00:33:51,059
           The meter's in there.

722
00:33:51,095 --> 00:33:52,661
Oh, ta.                         
Won't be a minute.              

723
00:34:14,084 --> 00:34:15,550
  What the hell are you doing?  

724
00:34:15,586 --> 00:34:16,852
I'm so sorry.                   

725
00:34:16,887 --> 00:34:19,588
I was just seeing               
who made your armchair.         

726
00:34:19,623 --> 00:34:21,223
I really like it, see.          

727
00:34:21,258 --> 00:34:22,925
It's exactly                    
what I've been looking for.     

728
00:34:22,960 --> 00:34:25,093
          -Get out.             
          -Definitely.          

729
00:34:26,397 --> 00:34:28,397
            You're lucky I don't
            report you.         

730
00:34:33,304 --> 00:34:35,737
It really is                    
a lovely chair.                 

731
00:34:59,830 --> 00:35:02,097
            -Ta-da.             
            -[gasps]            

732
00:35:02,132 --> 00:35:04,032
    [Lu]                        
    They're definitely fake.    

733
00:35:06,070 --> 00:35:08,337
            So he was in there. 
            You're a genius, Lu.

734
00:35:08,372 --> 00:35:10,806
See, Phil Layman may be a thief,
but he's not a murderer.        

735
00:35:11,709 --> 00:35:13,075
                           Lola.

736
00:35:13,110 --> 00:35:16,912
  [Lu] Oh, well,                
  there's a miraculous recovery.

737
00:35:16,947 --> 00:35:19,181
    [Sebastian]                 
    She knows we're onto her.   

738
00:35:19,216 --> 00:35:20,449
             Right.             

739
00:35:20,484 --> 00:35:22,551
Let's see who she runs to.      

740
00:35:22,586 --> 00:35:24,086
There you go.                   

741
00:35:24,121 --> 00:35:26,388
 A cup of builders works wonders
 in these situations.           

742
00:35:26,423 --> 00:35:27,889
                  Thanks, Frank.

743
00:35:27,925 --> 00:35:29,291
So, what now?                   

744
00:35:29,326 --> 00:35:32,461
      I'm going to get the first
      flight back to the States.

745
00:35:32,496 --> 00:35:33,895
What, you're giving up?         

746
00:35:33,931 --> 00:35:35,530
             Well, like you say,

747
00:35:35,566 --> 00:35:37,299
         there's a lot          
         of Elizabeth Hathaways,

748
00:35:37,334 --> 00:35:38,834
            and I'm out of cash.

749
00:35:38,869 --> 00:35:42,771
 So I can't exactly afford to   
 hire you to help me now, can I?

750
00:35:44,508 --> 00:35:46,308
Well, never mind.               

751
00:35:46,343 --> 00:35:47,776
You gave it your best shot.     

752
00:35:51,048 --> 00:35:53,248
    I have got the strongest    
    of feelings                 

753
00:35:53,283 --> 00:35:55,750
       that I know              
       that woman Theresa.      

754
00:35:55,786 --> 00:35:57,285
[sighs]                         
Yeah, but to be fair,           

755
00:35:57,321 --> 00:35:59,087
you swore blind                 
I was your nephew.              

756
00:35:59,123 --> 00:36:00,322
                    That's true.

757
00:36:00,357 --> 00:36:02,457
You're a nice fella,            
but your hunches are rubbish.   

758
00:36:02,493 --> 00:36:03,925
   It's a fair cop, governor.   

759
00:36:03,961 --> 00:36:05,260
       -[laughs]                
       -[cell phone rings]      

760
00:36:05,295 --> 00:36:06,628
Oh.                             

761
00:36:09,566 --> 00:36:10,932
                Did Sebastian   
                get in the flat?

762
00:36:10,968 --> 00:36:13,568
     He did, and found hairs    
     from Leon's wig            

763
00:36:13,604 --> 00:36:14,936
     under Lola's armchair.     

764
00:36:14,972 --> 00:36:16,138
                 You're kidding.

765
00:36:16,173 --> 00:36:17,706
                       Nice one.

766
00:36:17,741 --> 00:36:20,208
  -Does she suspect anything?   
  -She's on her bike. Literally.

767
00:36:20,244 --> 00:36:21,643
       Just pulled into         
       Ridgemead car park.      

768
00:36:21,678 --> 00:36:23,145
                  I'm on my way.

769
00:36:23,180 --> 00:36:25,981
     -Any chance of a lift?     
     -Sure.                     

770
00:36:26,016 --> 00:36:27,849
   [camera shutters clicking]   

771
00:36:34,791 --> 00:36:36,625
          For services rendered.

772
00:36:40,230 --> 00:36:42,063
Well, that's her debts paid.    

773
00:36:42,933 --> 00:36:44,933
       [car engine starts]      

774
00:36:48,939 --> 00:36:52,374
    Glad to see you             
    back on your feet, Lola.    

775
00:36:52,409 --> 00:36:55,243
 -Can you move your car, please?
 -I don't think DI Marlowe      
 would thank her.               

776
00:36:55,279 --> 00:36:57,145
          [Lu]                  
          And she is on her way.

777
00:36:57,180 --> 00:36:59,047
What's all this about?          

778
00:36:59,082 --> 00:37:01,783
      This is about you two     
      murdering Diana,          

779
00:37:01,818 --> 00:37:03,318
     and then framing Phil.     

780
00:37:03,353 --> 00:37:05,220
              What?             

781
00:37:05,255 --> 00:37:08,089
    I know you both hated Diana.
    Maybe with good reason.     

782
00:37:08,125 --> 00:37:10,392
You definitely                  
needed the cash.                

783
00:37:10,427 --> 00:37:12,360
    So the two of you came up   
    with the perfect murder.    

784
00:37:12,396 --> 00:37:14,095
          Well, nearly.         

785
00:37:15,399 --> 00:37:18,800
 Have you seen my phone?        
 I had it here. I'm sure of it. 

786
00:37:19,736 --> 00:37:22,137
         It'll turn up, darling.
         Always does.           

787
00:37:22,172 --> 00:37:25,206
    [Lu]                        
   <i> First you cooked up Lola's</i>  
   <i> fake compensation claim.</i>    

788
00:37:25,242 --> 00:37:28,510
      <i> Made the two of you</i>      
      <i> look like enemies.</i>       

789
00:37:28,545 --> 00:37:30,912
   <i> Next, you convinced Diana</i>   
   <i> to hire us.</i>                 

790
00:37:30,948 --> 00:37:32,547
   <i> You'd worked out</i>            
   <i> that private investigators</i>  

791
00:37:32,582 --> 00:37:34,416
       <i> would give you</i>          
       <i> the perfect alibi.</i>      

792
00:37:34,451 --> 00:37:37,786
 <i> Then, the day of the murder,</i>  
 <i> you got hold of Diana's phone.</i>

793
00:37:37,821 --> 00:37:39,487
         [phone chimes]         

794
00:37:45,996 --> 00:37:47,796
       <i> You set the trap.</i>       

795
00:37:51,568 --> 00:37:56,004
     [woman, on TV]             
    <i> There was no where to go</i>   
    <i> from that, then...</i>         

796
00:38:01,845 --> 00:38:03,778
  [indistinct chatter over TV]  

797
00:38:25,068 --> 00:38:27,669
     [paper money rustling]     

798
00:38:52,095 --> 00:38:54,095
       [phone line rings]       

799
00:39:01,471 --> 00:39:04,305
  [Lu, over phone]<i> Yeah, well,</i>  
 <i> as I said before, Mr. Tarsich,</i>

800
00:39:04,341 --> 00:39:05,974
      <i> patience is the key.</i>     

801
00:39:06,009 --> 00:39:08,143
      [Leon]                    
     <i> You don't understand.</i>     

802
00:39:08,178 --> 00:39:09,878
       We're not insured.       

803
00:39:09,913 --> 00:39:12,781
Well, not with the right policy,
anyway.                         

804
00:39:14,718 --> 00:39:16,384
    A few minutes later,        
    you returned to your flat   

805
00:39:16,419 --> 00:39:19,387
    and swapped places again.   

806
00:39:21,324 --> 00:39:23,258
    <i> Meanwhile, Phil arrived</i>    
    <i> at Arden Dreams,</i>           

807
00:39:23,293 --> 00:39:25,760
     <i> straight into the trap</i>    
     <i> that you'd set him.</i>       

808
00:39:35,305 --> 00:39:38,106
<i>Instead of reporting the crime,</i> 
<i>he took the money.</i>              

809
00:39:38,141 --> 00:39:40,108
      <i> Just as you'd hoped.</i>     

810
00:39:59,829 --> 00:40:01,362
           Which meant that when
           you led us to Phil,  

811
00:40:01,398 --> 00:40:02,530
        all the evidence        
        was laid out            

812
00:40:02,566 --> 00:40:05,400
      to make it look like      
      he was the killer.        

813
00:40:10,440 --> 00:40:13,274
Your partners certainly chose   
the wrong people to cheat on.   

814
00:40:13,310 --> 00:40:15,610
[police sirens blare distantly] 

815
00:40:26,122 --> 00:40:27,956
     Should leave you           
     on your own more often.    

816
00:40:27,991 --> 00:40:31,059
 -If you insist.                
 -Go on then, Frank. Rub it in. 

817
00:40:31,094 --> 00:40:32,860
         Yoda, you are.         

818
00:40:32,896 --> 00:40:34,095
           [all laugh]          

819
00:40:34,130 --> 00:40:35,897
     You're a great copper,     
     Christina.                 

820
00:40:35,932 --> 00:40:37,765
I'm hardly in a position        
to gloat, am I?                 

821
00:40:37,801 --> 00:40:38,967
        I didn't spot it.       

822
00:40:39,002 --> 00:40:40,568
         Thanks, Frank.         

823
00:40:40,604 --> 00:40:42,036
         See you later.         

824
00:40:42,072 --> 00:40:44,706
   Ah, hanging out with Martin's
   made you go all soft.        

825
00:40:44,741 --> 00:40:46,040
       Nah, don't be daft.      

826
00:40:46,076 --> 00:40:48,576
           Don't condone murder,
           obviously.           

827
00:40:48,612 --> 00:40:51,946
     But I do feel              
     a teeny bit sorry for Leon.

828
00:40:51,982 --> 00:40:54,215
  I mean, just hiding his       
  cross-dressing from his wife  

829
00:40:54,250 --> 00:40:56,484
    for all that time,          
    it must have been agony.    

830
00:40:56,519 --> 00:40:58,453
     Yeah. It's amazing         
     what people put up with    

831
00:40:58,488 --> 00:41:00,288
     just to keep a secret.     

832
00:41:04,394 --> 00:41:05,893
[Frank] We're looking           
for my grandmother.             

833
00:41:05,929 --> 00:41:07,295
She was called                  
Elizabeth Hathaway.             

834
00:41:07,330 --> 00:41:08,696
She died in 1953.               

835
00:41:08,732 --> 00:41:11,499
         [Martin] Yeah. We think
         she may be my mother.  

836
00:41:11,534 --> 00:41:14,802
    [Theresa]                   
    Here's a little something   
    for your journey.           

837
00:41:14,838 --> 00:41:17,572
        Oh, gosh.               
        Thank you, ma'am.       

838
00:41:17,607 --> 00:41:19,874
[laughs]                        

839
00:41:19,909 --> 00:41:21,175
      The vicar's daughter.     

840
00:41:21,211 --> 00:41:23,277
 -[Lu] What?                    
 -We need to get to the airport.

841
00:41:24,214 --> 00:41:26,180
       Got to stop Martin.      

842
00:41:26,216 --> 00:41:27,382
                Come on, get in.

843
00:41:27,417 --> 00:41:29,017
         -No, after you.        
         -After you.            

844
00:41:29,052 --> 00:41:30,418
          Just get in.          

845
00:41:31,755 --> 00:41:33,654
            [knocks]            

846
00:41:39,496 --> 00:41:41,062
             [sighs]            

847
00:41:42,699 --> 00:41:44,999
What is it?                     

848
00:41:46,302 --> 00:41:49,270
      I understand why          
      you tried to hide it.     

849
00:41:50,607 --> 00:41:53,608
    I mean, your father had     
    a reputation to protect.    

850
00:41:53,643 --> 00:41:55,076
         [gasps softly]         

851
00:41:56,546 --> 00:41:58,279
I don't...                      

852
00:41:58,314 --> 00:42:00,915
    I-- I don't know what...    

853
00:42:00,950 --> 00:42:02,984
   what you're talking about.   

854
00:42:03,019 --> 00:42:04,919
[Frank]                         
Theresa.                        

855
00:42:04,954 --> 00:42:08,623
       It's been 65 years.      

856
00:42:08,658 --> 00:42:11,058
       Don't you think it's time
       you admitted the truth?  

857
00:42:16,533 --> 00:42:18,132
             [sobs]             

858
00:42:18,168 --> 00:42:19,667
              Mama?             

859
00:42:19,702 --> 00:42:22,103
              Yes.              

860
00:42:22,138 --> 00:42:23,771
[cries]                         

861
00:42:37,387 --> 00:42:38,953
        [Frank]                 
        It was the 1950s.       

862
00:42:38,988 --> 00:42:41,823
If people found out that Theresa
got pregnant out of wedlock,    

863
00:42:41,858 --> 00:42:43,457
       there'd have been        
       a massive scandal.       

864
00:42:43,493 --> 00:42:46,160
     Especially with her dad    
     being the local rev.       

865
00:42:46,196 --> 00:42:48,563
        She was sent away       
        to have Martin.         

866
00:42:48,598 --> 00:42:50,698
   Her dad bribed a registrar   
   to put another woman's name  

867
00:42:50,733 --> 00:42:52,233
    on the birth certificate.   

868
00:42:52,268 --> 00:42:55,770
 Theresa suggested her recently 
 departed best friend, my nana. 

869
00:42:55,805 --> 00:42:57,538
Do you know what's great        
about all this,                 

870
00:42:57,574 --> 00:42:59,006
is that you can                 
find out from Theresa           

871
00:42:59,042 --> 00:43:00,808
everything you didn't know      
about your gran.                

872
00:43:00,844 --> 00:43:03,144
   I've already found out       
   everything I need to know.   

873
00:43:03,179 --> 00:43:08,082
      Apparently, my nana       
      was a superb dancer.      

874
00:43:08,117 --> 00:43:10,251
  Which, of course, where I get 
  my innate sense of...         

875
00:43:10,286 --> 00:43:11,686
            [grunts]            

876
00:43:11,721 --> 00:43:13,654
           ...rhythm.           

877
00:43:13,690 --> 00:43:15,823
            [laughs]            
            Cheers.             

878
00:43:15,859 --> 00:43:17,024
           [Lu laughs]          

